<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="488" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,438,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,381,438,465]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">Diagnostic remark.</emphasis>
Based on Golovatch (2014, 2015), contrary to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffman" authorityYear="1963" box="[948,1083,439,465]" class="Diplopoda" family="Paradoxosomatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="3" pageNumber="492" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Alogolykini">Alogolykini</taxonomicName>
which typically shows a nearly fully to very strongly reduced gonofemorite, coupled with a basally originating, long, thick, mostly rod-like solenomere, the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeekel" authorityYear="1968" box="[355,512,511,537]" class="Diplopoda" family="Paradoxosomatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polydrepanini">Polydrepanini</taxonomicName>
seems to be best characterized by a clearly elongate, mostly slender, sometimes twisted/helicoid gonofemorite (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[504,526,546,572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">fe</emphasis>
) and a more or less thin, mostly flagelliform, suberect, distal to subapical solenomere (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[223,242,583,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">sl</emphasis>
) often forming a conspicuous loop/curve (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[721,737,583,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">k</emphasis>
) near the base (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[970,1071,583,609]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–5" captionStart-1="FIGURES 6–8" captionStartId-0="4.[151,264,1129,1153]" captionStartId-1="5.[151,264,1153,1177]" captionTargetBox-0="[156,1435,186,1103]" captionTargetBox-1="[159,1429,188,1127]" captionTargetId-0="figure-22@4.[151,1436,179,1103]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@5.[151,1436,181,1129]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–5. Grammorhabdus asperrimus Carl, 1932. 1. Male leg 1, lateral view. 2. Male leg 2, lateral view. 3. Entire left gonopod, mesal view. 4, 5. Distal half of left gonopod, lateral view. 1–4: after Carl (1932), 5: after Jeekel (1980B). Abbreviations: a and b, apicomesal spines; ad, adenostyle; ca, cannula; cx, coxite; fe, femorite; k, basal loop of solenomere; lo, lateral lobe; pfe, prefemoral portion; sl, solenomere; sph, solenophore. Drawn not to scale." captionText-1="FIGURES 6–8. Grammorhabdus fissus (Sankaran &amp; Sebastian, 2018). 6, 7. Right gonopod, ventral and mesal views, respectively. 8. Distal half of right gonopod, lateral view. After Sankaran and Sebastian (2018). Abbreviations: a and b, apicomesal lobes; ad, adenostyle; ca, cannula; cx, coxite; fe, femorite; k, basal loop of solenomere; lo, lateral lobe; pfe, prefemoral portion; sl, solenomere; sph, solenophore; su, distofemoral sulcus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (6, 7) and 0.2 mm (8)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709512" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5709516" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5709512/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5709516/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">Figs 3–8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
